The key thing we see from our side is that while individual miner UIDs do fluctuate epoch-to-epoch, the actual miner groups (based on coldkeys/IPs) are very stable in the top ranks. @zeus・18 
# **Coming Monday**: ⚡Release 1.4.0 - 🚀 Response speed! ⚡
We are hard at work building** valuable products & APIs** around our subnet, querying miners through the validator proxy. One of our potential clients highly values the ability to respond at lightning speeds, anywhere on the globe. As a part of this, we recently set up a second validator in Oregon in addition to our existing validator in Frankfurt, ensuring a better global spread. Since miners currently have no incentive to be fast, some requests take almost the full 10 second time-out to complete. This is not an acceptable time-window for a production API, so we are making some changes. With this new update, response time will be part of the reward incentive!

**What will be changed exactly?**
- 30% of your score will be based on response speed. This is again done through a curved distribution. Here the median response time of all miners for that challenge is computed, and you will be awarded a score-component between 0 (slow) and 1 (fast) depending on how much better/worse you are than the median score!
- We also changed the curving mechanism for all scoring slightly. Currently, if there were only a few unique predictions, miners could get a score of 0 despite being very close to the best performer. This could make the incentive jump around a lot. To remedy this, the ranges for the score-curving are now based on multiples of the average score, not on the min/max of the scores.
- Networking improvements, to ensure your response time is influenced as little as possible by validator networking capacity. This should also drastically reduce the number of penalties through timeout! ( @JUP )

**Action for Miners:**
Your current code will definitely still work! But you will able to get even better performance by optimizing your prediction code for efficiency🚀  
The code is already live on Testnet! https://github.com/Orpheus-AI/Zeus/pull/37

No all validator are not equally important/powerful for the final emission. Their relevative 'power' is determined by a combination of their stake and vTrust (higher is more powerful for both). Just to be clear, none of this is Zeus specific, this is something that is the same across all subnets and decided by Bittensor. You can see stake and vTrust for all validators here:
https://taostats.io/subnets/18/metagraph?order=stake%3Adesc

Just one note.
VTrust doesn't affect weights. On the contrary, it reflects consensus. In short, only stake determines the "importance" of weights. Although there are a lot of nuances involved.
thanks guys

It doesn't affect the weights directly no. But to calculate the total incentive (i.e. what miners see on the metagraph), vTrust does matter. vTrust is an indication for consensus, which in turn affects validator 'power'. 

Simply put, a validator with a lot of stake but very low vTrust can have the same influence on a miner's final metagraph rank as a validator will less stake but higher vTrust. The complete story is very technical, but a mathmatical formulation can be found here: https://github.com/opentensor/subtensor/blob/main/docs/consensus.md

Hey everyone, just read through and definitely understand the perspective and appreciate the miner feedback here. There has been a variety of issues brought up, and I'll do my best to summarize and then provide details on how they can be addressed:

1. API Connection Issues with OpenMeteo: This issue is outside the control of the Zeus team. We will reach out to the OpenMeteo team to bring up this connection error and see if they can help resolve it, but ultimately, it depends on their response.
2. Incentive Mechanism and Fairness: We acknowledge the concerns about the balance between speed and accuracy in the current incentive mechanism (70-30 split). While speed is important for potential clients, we understand the frustration when accuracy is compromised. We are exploring options to refine this balance, possibly by introducing a response time threshold to penalize excessively slow responses without undermining accuracy. However, we need to serve the api in a responsive manner to grow the business and speed is very important and is important to incentivize
3. Validator-Owned Miners and Collusion: We take allegations of validator-owned miners manipulating scores seriously. All validators have high vTRUST, indicating consensus on rankings. However, we will investigate any specific claims (e.g., UID 167) to ensure fairness. If proven, appropriate actions will be taken. Any evidence of this happening, please reach out to @Wouter | Ørpheus AI and @Egill | Ørpheus AI or myself. 
4. Network Latency and Response Times: The discrepancy between local response times (e.g., 0.01s) and network-recorded times (e.g., 0.3-0.4s) is a known challenge. Network latency is an engineering issue that all miners must address to remain competitive. We encourage optimizing network communication patterns. We are also looking into ways to mitigate this impact on scoring. As mentioned previously performance is critical, but incentizing miners setup with a close proximity to validators is not the intended behavior. 
5. Lack of Transparency and Responsiveness: Apologize for any perception of lack of transparency or responsiveness. We are committed to addressing these issues openly. We simply cannot pause registrations, this is a protocol-level restriction. However, we are actively engaging with the community and considering suggestions, such as database architectures for long-term improvements. Propose having an AMA or other type of open forum where we can all meet and discuss later this week or early next week. Furthermore, we will focus on improving communication and adhering to extreme transparency and responsiveness. 
6. Suggestions for Improvement: We appreciate the suggestions, like setting a response time threshold and exploring database solutions. While short-term implementation may not be feasible, these ideas are on our roadmap. We encourage continued dialogue and collaboration to enhance the subnet.
7. General Dissatisfaction: We understand the frustration and the broader concerns about the direction of Bittensor subnets. Our goal is to create a useful and fair system for all participants, ultimately driving the best weather prediction service in the world. We are here to listen and adapt where possible. If you disagree with our approach, remember that the subnet is open source, and you are welcome to fork it and run it your way. 

Again, appreciate the feedback. Let's keep the discussion productive and focus on solutions. Zeus team has been absolutely grinding the past 3 months on this and begining to see some really valuable and amazing outputs, which heavily rely on the miners (all of you!). 

Zeus is committed to improving the subnet for everyone involved. Thank you for your patience and understanding.

⚡Release 1.4.1 - Threshold efficiency reward, better logging and documentation 📚⚡
@zeus・18 

This is a relatively small update, bringing a change to only the efficiency (response speed) part of the scoring mechanism. Additionally, some of the documentation has been updated and the validator setup has been improved for validators running on AWS.

What has changed for miners?
Previously, when scoring response speed, the best possible score threshold was calculated based on the median response speed. We did this initially as we did not yet know what speeds live miners would achieve. After having run the update for a week, we have now decided that a speed of 0.2 seconds or above is fast enough, meaning if a miner responds within that timeframe, they receive a perfect speed-score. This will prevent miners from getting boosted too much for being in the same datacentre as a single validator. The bottom threshold for the worst speed is still calculated based on the median, to account for networking instabilities.

For validators
For existing validators, no changes other than pulling the latest version of the codebase are required. For new validators, please reach out to us on Discord, and we will help with setting up and choosing a validator location, to ensure a global spread.

The Zeus team

I believe the current top miners are using the same data and running the same code, so I don’t understand why their results differ. Why do some miners consistently stay at the top while others fall behind? I’ve raised this question before, several of our miners have been dropping down periodically despite having no issues. You mentioned that this problem was fully resolved, but it still seems to persist. What are your thoughts on miners using identical data and code receiving different scores?

You're absolutely right. To be more precise, the issue is the **variance in the sampled queries**.

Due to the random sampling, each miner receives a slightly different "batch" of work in any given period. Even if the models are identical, one miner might receive a set of queries that, by chance, are infinitesimally easier or faster to process, leading to a fractional improvement in their average score. As you said, because the scores are so incredibly close, the final weights are hypersensitive to this statistical variance.

This is also why the repeated claims about "special protection" can be frustrating. When we investigate, we see what the data shows: the average scores between these groups are nearly identical. On top of that, the idea that certain miners "never get deregistered" is incorrect—we have seen and can confirm that neurons from the coldkeys you pointed out have been deregistered from the network.

The core issue isn't a flaw in the miners' performance or a conspiracy, but a side-effect of the ranking's sensitivity to minor, random fluctuations. Making the scoring less susceptible to this is a key area we're looking to improve.

After analysing the current performances on our subnet and discussing with our miners, we have decided to slightly reduce the importance of the response speed.

**What changes?**
- Responsive speed now makes up **20%** of the incentive, with the remaining **80%** focussed on RMSE
- A response speed of **0.4 seconds** of less is now considered a perfect score for this component
- The wind speed baseline has improved slighty, also simplying the respective OpenMeteo code

The codebase should now be compatible with a Torch-based metagraph, although running a Numpy based metagraph is still preferred.
